description: From Middle English wymble, wymbel. Compare Middle Dutch wimmel, Middle Low German wimel, wemel.

entries.meaning: Any of various hand tools for boring holes.

description: From Middle English wimblen, from the noun (above). Compare Middle Low German wemelen.

verbs.description: wimble (third-person singular simple present wimbles, present participle wimbling, simple past and past participle wimbled)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To truss hay with a wimble.
examples: “Tending thrashing-machine and wimbling haybonds, and saying ‘Hoosh!’ to the cocks and hens when they go upon your seeds, and planting Early Flourballs and Thompson’s Wonderfuls with a dibble.”

entries.meaning: To bore or pierce, as with a wimble.
examples: […]  a foot soldier had hid himself  […]  and being greedy of prey, crept into the vault, and cut so much of the velvet pall that covered the great body, as he judged would hardly be missed, and wimbled also a hole thro’ the said coffin that was largest  […]

adjectives.description: wimble (comparative more wimble, superlative most wimble)

examples: He was so wimble, and so wight,
From bough to bough he lepped light,
